Based on the indentation in your code, it looks like your intention is that if there is a division by zero error, `calificacion` is set to 1 and then the exception handling is done.  That is not, however, what you&#39;ve written.  Everything between `EXCEPTION` and `END process_data` is part of your exception handler.  So you only insert into `tabla_ac` if there was a division by zero error.

            EXCEPTION 
            WHEN e_div_zero THEN
                calificacion := -1;
                
            INSERT INTO TABLA_AC AC (AC.AC_REGLA, AC.AC_FECHA_CALIFICACION, AC.AC_CALIFICACION, AC.AC_ARCHIVONOTAS_ID)
            VALUES (REGLA, TO_CHAR(SYSDATE, &#39;MM-DD-YYYY HH24:MI:SS&#39;), CALIFICACION, NOTAS_DATOS_ID_IN );
            
            FilasAfectadas:= SQL%RowCount;
            COMMIT;
        END PROCESS_DATA;

I expect that you intended something like this with an extra nested PL/SQL block

    BEGIN
      BEGIN -- BEGIN the new nested PL/SQL block
        IF (CORRECTAS_IN IS NOT NULL AND ERRONEAS_IN IS NOT NULL) THEN
          &lt;&lt;rest of your code&gt;&gt;
        END IF;
      EXCEPTION 
        WHEN e_div_zero THEN
          calificacion := -1;
      END; -- END the nested PL/SQL block

      INSERT INTO TABLA_AC AC (AC.AC_REGLA, AC.AC_FECHA_CALIFICACION, AC.AC_CALIFICACION, AC.AC_ARCHIVONOTAS_ID)
        VALUES (REGLA, TO_CHAR(SYSDATE, &#39;MM-DD-YYYY HH24:MI:SS&#39;), CALIFICACION, NOTAS_DATOS_ID_IN );

      FilasAfectadas:= SQL%RowCount;
      COMMIT;
    END PROCESS_DATA;

A couple of other comments not related to your immediate problem..

1) If you want to have an `IF` statement with multiple `ELSE` conditions, use `ELSIF` rather than starting new `IF` statements.  That way you don&#39;t end up with half a dozen `END IF` statements in a row.  It makes much more sense to say

    IF &lt;&lt;condition 1&gt;&gt; THEN
      &lt;&lt;do something&gt;&gt;
    ELSIF &lt;&lt;condition 2&gt;&gt; THEN
      &lt;&lt;do something else&gt;&gt;
    ELSIF &lt;&lt;condition 3&gt;&gt; THEN
      &lt;&lt;do a third thing&gt;&gt;
    ELSE
      &lt;&lt;do a final thing&gt;&gt;
    END IF;

2) If you have a `COMMIT` in your procedure, the vast majority of the runtime will be the result of trying to run 100,000 commits.  That&#39;s going to take hundreds of times more time than inserting 100,000 rows and doing a single commit in the outer procedure.  

It does not appear that your code is designed to be re-entrant so it is probably functionally problematic to have interim commits as well.  What happens if you&#39;ve processed 50,000 rows and your code throws an exception?  You&#39;d have no apparent way to restart the process at row 50,001 so if you re-ran your loop, you&#39;d end up with 150,000 rows in `tabla_ac` rather than 100,000 which is unlikely to be what you wanted.

